---
// v25 GAMMA — Series landing for Who Steals from Children, the
// state-by-state prosecutorial-history series. Volume 1 lands first;
// future volumes carry the same series template.
//
// Landings do NOT carry the per-chapter pre-publication banner (banner
// gates on kind === 'essay' in [slug].astro). They do carry the
// site-wide pre-publication footer via BaseLayout.
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getServerSupabase } from '../../lib/supabase';

export const prerender = false;

// v32 — published-review count for the footer Reviews link. Same pattern
// as on the other in-house book landings.
let reviewCount = 0;
try {
  const supabase = getServerSupabase(Astro);
  const { data: work } = await supabase
    .from('works')
    .select('id')
    .eq('slug', 'who-steals-from-children-vol-1')
    .maybeSingle();
  if (work?.id) {
    const { count } = await supabase
      .from('reviews')
      .select('id', { count: 'exact', head: true })
      .eq('work_id', work.id)
      .eq('is_published', true);
    if (typeof count === 'number') reviewCount = count;
  }
} catch {
  // swallow
}
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Who Steals from Children — A Series · America's School Trust Library"
  description="A state-by-state prosecutorial-history series naming the actors, dates, dollars, and documents in each live trust-breach case. Volume 1 — Oregon and the Elliott — is the case-in-chief."
  sourceId="reading-who-steals-from-children-series"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">Reading Room · Companion Series</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2"><em>Who Steals from Children</em> — A Series</h1>
    <p class="kicker text-slate-600">
      A state-by-state prosecutorial-history series. One volume per active breach.
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Who Steals from Children</em> is the case-by-case prosecutorial record
      of how America's school-land trusts are being broken in the present tense.
      One state per volume. Each volume names the actors, the dates, the dollars,
      and the documentary record. The series is the live applied form of the
      diagnostic frame in
      <a href="/reading/the-librarys-argument/">the Library's Argument</a> — the
      ship-and-anchors record placed against a specific trustee, a specific
      removal, and a specific year.
    </p>

    <p>
      The series title — <em>Who Steals from Children</em> — comes to us from
      Jim Petersen of <em>Evergreen</em>, who used the phrase in a 2025 phone
      call with Dave Sullivan when the two were discussing what Oregon had done
      to the Elliott. Petersen put the question in the register the school-trust
      record requires: not <em>what went wrong</em>, but <em>who stole from
      whom</em>, named.
    </p>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <section class="series-volumes mt-8" aria-label="Volumes in this series">
      <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
        Volumes
      </h2>

      <article class="volume-card mt-4">
        <p class="card-kicker">Volume 1 · Oregon</p>
        <h3 class="card-title">
          <em>Who Steals from Children: Volume 1 — Oregon and the Elliott</em>
        </h3>
        <p class="card-byline">
          Dave Sullivan
        </p>
        <p class="card-length">Foreword · Preface · 13 chapters · Documentary Record</p>
        <p class="card-blurb">
          How the State of Oregon has spent thirty-five years removing a
          billion-dollar working trust asset from the Common School Fund —
          and how the schoolchildren of Oregon and their advocates have
          caught it in the act. The case-in-chief that the Library's
          two-volume diagnostic frame is built to handle.
        </p>
        <a href="/reading/who-steals-from-children-vol1-elliott/" class="card-cta">
          Open Volume 1 →
        </a>
      </article>

      <p class="forthcoming mt-6 text-sm italic text-slate-500">
        Future volumes are forthcoming as each state's record is assembled.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <section class="readers-edition mt-8" aria-labelledby="readers-edition-heading">
      <h2 id="readers-edition-heading" class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
        About the Reader's Edition
      </h2>

      <p class="mt-4">
        Every volume of <em>Who Steals from Children</em> is written here as
        a Reader's Edition — a first-person, scene-grounded account written for
        the people whose children are the named beneficiaries of the school-land
        trusts each volume documents. Parents. School-district administrators.
        Civic-engaged general readers. The constituency whose absence from the
        room is the reason these trusts have been allowed to drift in the first
        place.
      </p>

      <p class="mt-4">
        The Reader's Edition is built around the journey the author actually
        took to arrive at the case the volume documents. The documentary
        record — appraisals, court filings, attorney general opinions,
        legislative votes, internal agency correspondence — is woven into
        the body of each chapter as the author encountered it, and is set off
        in boxed insets where a reader who wants to know the underlying
        doctrine or the precise language of a document can find it without
        slowing the narrative for the reader who does not.
      </p>

      <p class="mt-4">
        The volumes in this series are written to be read straight through in
        one or two long sittings. They are not legal treatises. They are not
        academic histories. They are the case as the citizen who brought it
        learned it, ordered the way the citizen learned it, with the
        documents on the page where the reader meets them.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <p class="mt-8 text-sm text-slate-600">
      <a href="/reading/">← Back to the Reading Room</a>
    </p>

    <p class="reviews-link mt-4 text-sm text-slate-500">
      <a href="/reading/who-steals-from-children-vol-1/reviews/">Reviews ({reviewCount})</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .volume-card {
    background: var(--linen-card, #fafaf7);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-border, #e5e7eb);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 1.5rem 1.5rem 1.25rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .card-kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .card-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    line-height: 1.35;
    margin: 0 0 0.4rem;
  }
  .card-byline {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: #475569;
    margin: 0 0 0.25rem;
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .card-length {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: #64748b;
    margin: 0 0 0.85rem;
  }
  .card-blurb {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #334155;
    margin: 0 0 1.1rem;
  }
  .card-cta {
    align-self: flex-start;
    color: #1d4ed8;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
  }
  .card-cta:hover {
    color: #1e40af;
  }
</style>
